# The following is a reference for the index and alphabet.
alphabet = dict(zip(string.ascii_lowercase, range(1,27)))

def get_alphabet(alphabet, index):
    """
    Retrieve the key (alphabet) given its value (index).
    """
    for i, j in alphabet.items():
        if j == index:
            return i
    # If index is not existent (not in range(1, 27))
    return None
    
print(alphabet)

# Build the same convnet model to apply to the EMNIST dataset
model_emnist_convnet = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.Input(shape=(28, 28, 1)),
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
  tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
  tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(27, activation="softmax"),
])

Part 2-5

You should have found that while the EMNIST Letters are harder to learn than the MNIST digits, switching to a different network architecture led to a significant increase in model performance.

You may have noticed, however, that the training process was slower. This means that experiments take longer, and mistakes can be costly. While plotting a learning curve when training has finished can help diagnose problems, ideally you will want to see updates during the training process.

In order to avoid dead-ends while adjusting and tuning your model, TensorFlow includes the TensorBoard tool and the TensorBoard notebook extension for this purpose. While the examples show Keras models, PyTorch supports TensorBoard as well.

Add TensorBoard support to the CNN model you run in Part 1, and add TensorBoard to your notebook to visualize the training process.

  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size = (3,3), kernel_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001), bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001)),
  tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
  tf.keras.layers.Activation('relu'),
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2,2), strides = (2,2)),
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size = (3,3), kernel_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001), bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001)),
  tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
  tf.keras.layers.Activation('relu'),
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(96, kernel_size = (3,3), kernel_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001), bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001)),
  tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
  tf.keras.layers.Activation('relu'),
  tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, kernel_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001), bias_regularizer = tf.keras.regularizers.l2(0.000001)),
  tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
  tf.keras.layers.Activation('relu'),

# Using the covnet model
model_emnist_convnet = tf.keras.Sequential([
  tf.keras.Input(shape=(28, 28, 1)),
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
  tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3, 3), activation="relu"),
  tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)),
  tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
  tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
  tf.keras.layers.Dense(27, activation="softmax"),
])

model_emnist_convnet.summary()

# Initialisation
batch_size = 128
epochs = 15

# Compile the model
model_emnist_convnet.compile(loss = "sparse_categorical_crossentropy",
                             optimizer = "adam",
                             metrics = ["accuracy"])

# Train the model
model_emnist_convnet.fit(resized_x_train, y_train_labels, batch_size = batch_size,
                         epochs = epochs, validation_data = (resized_x_test, y_test_labels),
                         callbacks = [tensorboard_callback_e_cnn])
# Start TensorBoard
%tensorboard --logdir logs/fit

As seen on tensorboard's epoch loss chart and the numbers itself, the model seems to finally adjust itself and having more number of epochs might actually allow the model to perform better, but due to lack of GPU and time, this can be investigate further into the future

The value that cam from reusing a pre-trained model is worse, but with a regular covnet model, then the accuracy seems to perform fine and expected.
